Comment:
Bernie needs to turn his attention to the general election. He could win in a landslide by addressing the following:

As higher ed tuition and fees have increased at double the rate of inflation every year, on average, for more than 40 years resulting in average annual incomes needing to exceed $ 210,000 to have kept pace, commit to not providing loans or loan guarantees to any student attending a school that increases their tuition and fees more than 1% / year for the next 10 years. This would make the GOP's heads explode as Sanders chose to side with students, their families, and the taxpayers over the academic elites that have brought us this scandal.

Scrap Head Start and start over as HHS has shown Head Start to have no lasting impact. This would show the voters he will not tolerate totally failed programs just because they sound good.

Reverse the policies over the last 7 years that have led to middle class incomes declining and most of the economic improvement centered on the top 10% of wage earners and wealth holders and nearly all on the top 25% by undoing the record increases in regulations and regressive taxes. These are the people he needs to win and actually siding with them is crucial.

Eliminate the Dept. of Education which has spent many trillions as its direct contribution to a tripling of real per student spending over the last 40 years with no performance increases (and remedial reading, writing, and math being the fastest growing classes in higher ed). He should advocate that the savings from eliminating a department that has accomplished nothing be devoted to the infrastructure he and his party speak of being so important. This would gather large numbers of votes.

We are now told there are 17 million children (suddenly up from 14.5 million) that are going hungry or at risk of going hungry. This despite 18 federal needs based food programs, more at the state and local level, 450,000 churches, most of which have persistent or emergency food assistance, 1,000s of local food only charities, large charities with food assistance programs, and of course, extended families. She could leverage off this admission of failure to completely revamp our food assistance programs such that they would not leave 17 million children at risk.

Only special interests vested in the status quo of these failed programs and departments could argue against this.

These pro child, pro education, pro middle class, and pro lower income policies would propel Bernie back into the race.
